==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Purloin
<hw>Pur*loin"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Purloined</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Purloining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>purloignier</ets>, <ets>porloignier</ets>, to retard, delay;
<ets>pur</ets>, <ets>por</ets>, <ets>pour</ets>, for (L. <ets>pro</ets>)
+ <ets>loin</ets> far, far off (L. <ets>longe</ets>). See
<er>Prolong</er>, and cf. <er>Eloign</er>.]</ety> <def>To take or carry
away for one's self; hence, to steal; to take by theft; to
filch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Had from his wakeful custody <qex>purloined</qex>⟦br⟧
The guarded gold.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>when did the muse from Fletcher scenes <qex>purloin</qex> ?</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purloin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Purloin
<hw>Pur*loin"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To practice theft; to
steal.</def> <rj><au>Titus ii. 10.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purloiner</ent>⟦br⟧
